title: Enhanced Quality in Primary Care for Elders With Diabetes and Dementia
description_brief: The purpose of this study is to develop and test a care quality improvement intervention featuring use of consensus decisional guidance for the medical management of diabetes (DM) in patients with Alzheimer's disease and related dementia (ADRD) in primary care, provider (PCP) workflow enhancements supported by a panel manager(PM) for workflow support, electronic health record (EHR) decision support and feedback, and PCP collaborative learning.

groups.title: Intervention (INT)
groups.description:
(10 clinic sites and \~500 patients) which includes practice guidelines for clinicians, provider education, electronic health record support for quality DM-ADRD care, information about community/clinical resources, ongoing targeted provider feedback, and a panel manager (PM)

EQUIPED-ADRD Intervention: (10 clinic sites and \~500 patients) which includes practice guidelines for clinicians, provider education, electronic health record support for quality DM-ADRD care, information about community/clinical resources, ongoing targeted provider feedback, and a panel manager (PM)

groups.title: Control (CON)
groups.description:
During training the CON providers will be encouraged to do cognitive screening as well as follow the guidelines in general.

Control (CON): Will use current guidelines for primary care treatment with Diabetes and Dementia

outcomeMeasures.title: Percent of Patients Who Reach Consensus Target HBA1c
outcomeMeasures.description: Percentage of patients with normal HbA1c (\>=7 and \<=8.5) at the end of the trial after completing the 24-month Follow-up and who had reported values in their electronic health record within 6 months of study completion.

explanation_target: Reason: The study tests a care quality improvement (behavioral) intervention to improve primary-care management of diabetes in patients with Alzheimer’s disease and related dementias — using consensus decisional guidance, panel managers, EHR decision support/feedback, and PCP collaborative learning (intended effect = better diabetes care/HbA1c management), not a drug or biologic. citeturn0search0turn0search4

Act: Key extracted details — Intervention name: EQUIPED-ADRD (behavioral QI intervention). Intervention components: practice guidelines/decisional guidance for clinicians, provider education, EHR support, panel manager, targeted provider feedback, and PCP collaborative learning. Control = behavioral/usual-care training. Primary outcome focuses on percent of patients reaching a consensus target HbA1c (no investigational drug or biologic is listed). citeturn0search2turn0search0

Web search results supporting extraction: 1) Clinical trial registration and intervention description (EQUIPED-ADRD; NCT03723707) showing behavioral interventions and HbA1c outcome. citeturn0search0turn0search2 2) Grant description (R21/R33) describing development/testing of a QI program for DM-ADRD with consensus decisional guidance, panel manager, and EHR support. citeturn0search4

Reflect: Classification check — this is not a pharmacologic trial (no drug or placebo, interventions are behavioral/organizational/health IT). Therefore it does not fit the four therapeutic categories (disease-targeted biologic, disease-targeted small molecule, cognitive enhancer, or neuropsychiatric symptom improvement). The correct classification is 'N/A'.
